parse.title: List of geological features on Iapetus

text.*:
This article does not cite any sources. Please help improve this article by adding citations to reliable sources. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (October 2015) (Learn how and when to remove this template message)

Most Iapetian geological features are named after characters and locations in the Old French epic poem The Song of Roland, specifically the English translation by Dorothy L. Sayers.

Contents

  • 1 Montes
  • 2 Regiones
  • 3 Terrae
  • 4 Craters
  • 5 References
  • 6 External links

Montes[edit]

A mons /ˈmɒnz/, pl. montes /ˈmɒntiːz/, is a mountain.

Regiones[edit]

There is one named Iapetian regio /ˈriːdʒioʊ/ (area of distinct albedo difference), Cassini:

Regio Coordinate Named after Pronounced
Cassini Regio 28°06′S 92°36′W﻿ / ﻿28.1°S 92.6°W﻿ / -28.1; -92.6﻿ (Cassini Regio) Giovanni Cassini, discoverer of Iapetus /kəˈsiːni/

The adjectival form is Cassinian /kəˈsɪniən/.

Terrae[edit]

There are two named Iapetian terrae /ˈtɛriː/ (large 'land' masses).

Terra Coordinate Diameter (km) Named after Pronounced
Roncevaux Terra 37°00′N 239°30′W﻿ / ﻿37.0°N 239.5°W﻿ / 37.0; -239.5 1284.0 Battle of Roncevaux Pass /rɒnsəˈvoʊ/
Saragossa Terra 45°00′S 180°00′W﻿ / ﻿45.0°S 180.0°W﻿ / -45.0; -180.0 2300.0 Saragossa, Spain /særəˈɡɒsə/

The adjectival form of Roncevaux is Roncesvallian.
